The culture of Vietnam (Vietnamese: **Văn hoá Việt Nam**, chữ Hán: **文化越南**) comprises the customs, traditions, and artistic expressions of the diverse peoples inhabiting the country. Situated within [Southeast Asia](/Southeast_Asia) and the [Sinosphere](/Sinosphere), Vietnamese culture has been profoundly shaped by centuries of [Chinese culture](/Chinese_culture) following the [1000 years of Northern Rule](/Vietnam_under_Chinese_rule) (111 BCE – 939 CE). From this era until the 19th century, [Classical Chinese](/Classical_Chinese) ( [Hán văn](/Literary_Chinese_in_Vietnam) ) served as the language of official writing. Between the 15th and 19th centuries, popular literature and folk songs were composed in the Vietnamese language using a native script derived from Chinese characters ( [chữ Nôm](/Ch%E1%BB%AF_N%C3%B4m) ). [4][5]  

After gaining independence in the 10th century, Vietnam embarked on a [southward expansion](/Nam_ti%E1%BA%BFn) that incorporated lands previously controlled by [Champa](/Champa) and the [Khmer](/Khmer_Empire), leaving a lasting imprint on the nation’s cultural mosaic. During the [French colonial period](/French_Indochina), [Catholicism](/Catholic_Church) was introduced, and a [Latin script](/Latin_script) — the [Vietnamese alphabet](/Vietnamese_alphabet) (Vietnamese: **chữ Quốc Ngữ**, literally “National Language Script”) — was promoted as the official writing system. [6]  

Characteristic elements of Vietnamese culture include ancestor veneration, deep respect for community and family, and a harmonious relationship with the natural environment. [7]  

