## Language  

**Main article:** [Vietnam § Languages](/Vietnam)  

Handwritten Vietnamese manuscripts illustrate the transition from [chữ Nôm](/Ch%E1%BB%AF_N%C3%B4m) to the modern [Vietnamese alphabet](/Vietnamese_alphabet).  

Vietnam ranks among the most linguistically diverse nations of [Southeast Asia](/Southeast_Asia). While [Vietnamese](/Vietnamese_language) holds official status, more than one hundred minority languages are spoken across the territory, belonging to five major families: [Austronesian](/Austronesian_languages), [Austroasiatic](/Austroasiatic_languages), [Hmong–Mien](/Hmong%E2%80%93Mien_languages), [Sino–Tibetan](/Sino%E2%80%93Tibetan_languages), and [Kra–Dai](/Kra%E2%80%93Dai_languages). [8] The language contains a substantial corpus of [Sino‑Vietnamese vocabulary](/Sino-Vietnamese_vocabulary).  

Phonologically, Vietnamese is an [Austroasiatic](/Austroasiatic) tongue marked by monosyllabic roots and tonal inflections. Its writing system originally employed [chữ Nôm](/Ch%E1%BB%AF_N%C3%B4m), a script based on Chinese characters, before evolving into the current [Vietnamese alphabet](/Vietnamese_alphabet). The alphabet incorporates a series of diacritics to denote tones: the [horn](/Horn_(diacritic)) for “ ơ ” and “ ư ”, the [circumflex](/Circumflex) for “ â ”, “ ê ”, and “ ô ”, the [breve](/Breve) for “ ă ”, and a bar through “ đ ”. Six tone marks—acute (á), grave (à), tilde (ã), dot below (ạ), and the neutral (a)—modify vowel quality. When typed on standard keyboards, digraphs such as “aa” produce “â”.  

