## Literature  

**Main article:** [Vietnamese literature](/Vietnamese_literature)  
**See also:** [Truyện tranh](/Truy%E1%BB%87n_tranh)  

A 19th‑century manuscript of *Lĩnh Nam chích quái* (Mysterious Tales of the Southern Realm) preserves a 15th‑century narrative, exemplifying early Vietnamese prose.  

The earliest extant written records in Vietnam appear after the [Han conquest of Nanyue](/Han_conquest_of_Nanyue) (111 BCE), when Old Chinese and Classical Chinese were inscribed on bricks and coins in the northern and central regions. The first surviving literary artifact is the Sanskrit [Võ Cạnh inscription](/V%C3%B5_C%E1%BA%A1nh_inscription) (4th century CE) near [Nha Trang](/Nha_Trang), attributed either to the [Funan](/Funan) or to the [Chamic](/Chamic) cultural sphere. This is followed by the [Old Cham](/Old_Cham) [Đông Yên Châu inscription](/%C4%90%C3%B4ng_Y%C3%AAn_Ch%C3%A2u_inscription) near [Trà Kiệu](/Tr%C3%A0_Ki%E1%BB%87u), erected by King [Bhadravarman I](/Bhadravarman_I) of Champa in the late 4th century, written in Old [Southern Brahmic](/Southern_Brahmic) script. It is recognized as the oldest extant epigraphic text of any Southeast Asian language, predating [Mon](/Mon_language), [Khmer](/Khmer_language), and [Malay](/Malay_language) by several centuries. [9]  

Literary production in Vietnam initially unfolded in [chữ Hán](/Literary_Chinese_in_Vietnam) and later in [chữ Nôm](/Ch%E1%BB%AF_N%C3%B4m). The latter script became dominant for poetic compositions from the 10th century onward. Up to the 21st century, two parallel literary streams existed: works composed in Classical Chinese—poems and prose that chronicled Vietnamese history and society—and works written in Nôm, primarily poetic works. [citation needed]  

From the 1920s onward, literature shifted predominantly to the national script (the [Vietnamese alphabet](/Vietnamese_alphabet)), ushering in radical innovations in form and genre—novels, modern poetry, short stories, and drama—while diversifying artistic orientations. The August Revolution catalyzed a surge in socially engaged writing, guided by the Vietnamese Communist Party’s cultural policy and focused on the lives of the people. [citation needed]  

Classical masterpieces include *The Tale of Kieu* (**[Truyện Kiều](/The_Tale_of_Kieu)**, by [Nguyễn Du](/Nguy%E1%BB%85n_Du)), *Complaint of a Palace Maid* (**[Cung Oán Ngâm Khúc](/Cung_o%C3%A1n_ng%C3%A2m_kh%C3%BAc)**, by [Nguyễn Gia Thiều](/Nguy%E1%BB%85n_Gia_Thi%E1%BB%81u)), *Lament of the Soldier’s Wife* (**[Chinh phụ ngâm](/Chinh_ph%E1%BB%A5_ng%C3%A2m)**, by [Đặng Trần Côn](/%C4%90%E1%BA%B7ng_Tr%E1%BA%A7n_C%C3%B4n)), and the *Poetry Collection* (**[Quốc âm Thi Tập](/Qu%E1%BB%91c_%C3%A2m_thi_t%E1%BA%ADp)**, by [Nguyễn Trãi](/Nguy%E1%BB%85n_Tr%E1%BB%A3i)**), all rendered in [chữ Quốc ngữ](/Vietnamese_alphabet). Notable female poets such as [Hồ Xuân Hương](/H%E1%BB%93_Xu%C3%A2n_H%C6%B0%C6%A1ng), [Đoàn Thị Điểm](/C%E4%B8%AD%E1%BB%A3n_Th%E1%BB%8B_%C4%90i%E1%BB%83m), and [Bà Huyện Thanh Quan](/B%C3%A0_Huy%E1%BB%87n_Thanh_Quan) further enriched the literary canon. [citation needed]  

Modern Vietnamese literature has traversed romanticism and realism, moved from wartime heroism to a nuanced portrayal of everyday life, and recently embraced English translations of Vietnamese fables. [10]  

