## Funeral Rites  

**• Traditional:** The funeral procession (**lễ đưa tang**) is scheduled with meticulous care; relatives, friends, and descendants escort the deceased along the route to the **[burial ground](/Burial_ground)**, dropping **[votives](/Votives)** en route. At the gravesite, the coffin is interred, and mourning observances unfold over a prescribed period: three days of lamentation, a ceremony after 49 days (**lễ chung thất**) when rice offerings cease, and a final rite after 100 days (**tốt khốc**) marking the conclusion of the mourning period. [citation needed][29][30][31]  

**• Modern:** Contemporary practice streamlines the ceremony, emphasizing the covering and placement of the body in a coffin, a simplified procession, and visits to the grave. [citation needed][32][33][34]  

Traditional attire for mourners comprises white garments and turbans; notable Vietnamese officials—such as Hồ Đắc Trung, Tôn Thất Hân, [Nguyễn Hữu Bài](/Nguy%E1%BB%85n_H%E1%BB%AFu_B%C3%A0i), and Đoàn Đình Duyệt—are depicted in the funeral portraiture of Emperor [Khải Định](/Kh%E1%BA%A3i_%C4%90%E1%BB%8Bnh).  

