## Traditional Clothing  

**Main article:** [Vietnamese clothing](/Vietnamese_clothing)  

Portrait of Nguyễn Quý Đức (1648–1720) wearing **[áo giao lĩnh](/a_o_giao_l%C4%A9nh)** illustrates the sartorial elegance of earlier eras.  

In feudal Vietnam, attire served as a marker of social stratification, and stringent **[dress codes](/Dress_code)** were enforced. [citation needed][35][36] Following the [Ming conquest of Vietnam](/Fourth_Chinese_domination_of_Vietnam), Ming officials imposed Chinese dress within a month; this policy, framed as “civilizing” the “barbarian” Vietnamese, paradoxically diminished the presence of Taoist institutions. [28][37]  

Later periods witnessed the emergence of distinct court garments, such as the **[áo tràng vạt](/a_o_trang_vat)**—a cross‑collared robe—later supplanted by the **[áo ngũ thân](/a_o_ngu_thân)** during the Nguyễn dynasty, which became obsolete. [29][30][31]  

The **[áo tứ thân](/a_o_t%E1%BB%A3_th%C3%A2n)** (“four‑part dress”) and its accompanying **[áo yếm](/a_o_y%E1%BB%A3m)** bodice represent ancient attire worn by commoner women. Peasants gradually adopted silk “pajama‑like” outfits: **[áo cánh]** in the north and **[áo bà ba](/a_o_b%C3%A0_ba)** in the south. [citation needed][32]  

Headgear varied across dynasties: the plain cloth wrap (**[Khăn vấn](/Kh%C4%83n_v%E1%BA%A5n)**) of the Nguyễn era, the hat **[Đinh Tự](/Đinh_T%E1%BB%B1)** of the Lê period, and the ubiquitous conical hat **[nón lá](/N%C3%B3n_l%C3%A1)**, which persists in two modern styles. Footwear traditionally consisted of barefoot activity for laborers, with wooden clogs or sandals reserved for formal occasions; shoes were the prerogative of the elite. [citation needed][33]  

Royal protocol reserved gold for emperors, while nobles donned red or purple; earlier dynasties—[Đinh dynasty](/C%E4%B8%ADinh_dynasty) and [Lý dynasty](/L%C3%BD_dynasty)—favored red and white, respectively. The imperial court maintained a repertoire of ceremonial gowns, each tied to specific rites. Although fashion regulations evolved dynasty by dynasty, fundamental principles endured. [citation needed][34]  

The **[áo dài](/a_o_d%C3%A0i)** stands as Vietnam’s most recognizable national costume, worn primarily by women; it comprises a long, fitted gown with side slits over tailored trousers. Initially promoted in the mid‑18th century by the rulers of **[Đàng Trong](/%C4%90%C3%A0ng_Trong)** to differentiate their subjects from those of **[Đàng Ngoài](/%C4%90%C3%A0ng_Ngo%C3%A0i)**, where **[áo tràng vạt]** and **[nhu quần]** prevailed. Today, white **[áo dài]** serves as the uniform for many secondary‑school girls, and certain professional sectors (e.g., hospitality, tourism) require its wearing. In everyday life, Western dress has largely supplanted traditional garb, except during festivals and ceremonial occasions. [citation needed][35]  

